The principle of IFE-based Mn(VII) assay was shown in Scheme 1. IFE usually requires a complementary overlap region between the absorption spectra of the absorbers and excitation or emission spectra of fluorophores. Accordingly, it is indispensable to select a proper absorber-fluorophore pair for performing an IFE-based FL assay. As depicted in Fig. 5e, the prepared N,P-CDs exhibited a strong fluorescence emission at 478 nm with the maximal excitation at 386 nm, and the multiple absorption peaks of the Mn(VII) were displayed, demonstrating a good overlap between emission spectrum of N,P-CDs and the absorption band of Mn(VII) to enable the IFE-based quenching to be highly efficient. Simultaneously, to further verify the IFE between Mn(VII) absorber and N,P-CDs fluorophore, the IFE-based fluorescence quenching can also be proven by fluorescence lifetime analysis. As can be seen from Fig. 5f, the FL decay curves of N,P-CDs in the absence and presence of Mn(VII) showed a high degree of consistency. The decay trace is fitted using biexponential functions as follows: Y(t) = A1exp(−t/τ1
                        ) + A2 exp(−t/τ2
                        ), where A1 and A2 are the corresponding amplitudes of time-resolved decay lifetime, respectively; τ1
                         and τ2
                         are the time constants of the two radiative decay channels. The average lifetime values of N, P-CDs and N, P-CDs /Mn(VII) are 8.60 ns and 8.68 ns, respectively (Table S2 ESI†), which further suggests the occurrence of IFE.

The relative viabilities of SMMC-7721 cells exposed to N,P-CDs were measured via the MTT assays to evaluate the cytotoxicity of N,P-CDs. More than 81.3% cells could survive after incubating with N,P-CDs even at concentrations rising from 0 to 1.2 mg mL−1 for 24 h (Fig. 6
                        ). These observations clearly indicated that the as-synthesized N,P-CDs had exerted lesser cytotoxic effects on the cells. The high stability and low cytotoxicity confirmed the imaging potential of the N,P-CDs. The above results highlight that the N,P-CDs become outstanding bio-probes and employ as fresh fluorescence makers that are responsible to cellular labeling and imaging applications. As depicted in Fig. 7
                        a, these cell-internalized N,P-CDs emitted remarkable blue (first panels), green (second panels) and red (third panels) emissions when they were stimulated by 405, 488 and 543 nm lasers, respectively. The merged images of first and second panels (fourth panels), first and third panels (fifth panels) and second and third panels (sixth panels) imply N,P-CDs are capable of permeating into cells. These CDs are mainly located in the cytoplasm and N,P-CDs and N,P-CDs/Mn(VII)-stained cells exhibit multicolor λex-dependent fluorescence under a laser of different wavelengths. Bestowed with the unique FL emission and good biocompatibility, the N,P-CDs are proposed to serve as a potential multicolor bio-labeling reagent. We next assessed the ability of the nanoprobe to image Mn(VII) in cell. The LSCM images of SMMC-7721 cells cultivated with N,P-CDs and N,P-CDs/Mn(VII) (Fig. 7b) retain good morphology, implying that N,P-CDs and N,P-CDs/Mn(VII) are biocompatible and have minimum cytotoxicity to cells. Moreover, cells stained with N,P-CDs initially exhibit apparent blue emissions (Fig.7, b1-b4). However, when Mn(VII) penetrated into SMMC-7721 cells culture fluid, the fluorescence signal is gradually weakened and finally can hardly be seen after 2 min (Fig. 7, b5-b8 and Fig. S8 ESI†). The intensities of 20 cells were measured at λex/λem of 405/422 ± 25 nm. (Fig. 7c). The fluorescence from N,P-CDs becomes dimmer with increasing concentration of exogenous Mn(VII), signifying N,P-CD is an efficient fluorescent probe for semiquantitatively monitoring the Mn(VII) in live cells.
